deck: An 1982 recording of a long-running theatrical adaptation of the Lewis Carrol tales. The protagonist was Meryl Streep in a change of pace from her mostly dramatic roles at the time.
name: Alice at the Palace

deck: An 1982 recording of a theatrical production by the Children's Theatre Company. The protagonist was young Annie Enneking. While a quality production it suffers somewhat from the raised voices of the actors, needed to reach a large live audience but hardly tolerated on film.
name: Alice in Wonderland

deck: A 2004 loose adaptation of the Lewis Carrol tales. Alice Liddell is an adult corporate worker, stuck in a dead-end job. Her life changes when a stranger first offers her a mysterious book and then runs away with it. She gives chase and finds herself in a Wonderland both bizarre and horrific.
name: Alice's Misadventures in Wonderland

deck: An 1999 live-action short film, loosely based on the Lewis Carroll tales. Alice is a twenty-year-old New Yorker, daughter to affluent parents. She is out of school and feeling directionless. While out on a bar, someone spikes her drink with a hallucinogen.Drugged and indoxicated she wanders around the City, encountering bizzare characters and trying to answer a seemingly simple question:  "Who are you, Alice?"
description: The actors involved have sevelar theatrical credits to their names but little to no cinematic ones. The exception is Korikova who has played in many Russian film production since 1989.
name: Alice Underground

deck: An 1985 film based partly on the life of Alice Pleasance Liddell (1852 - 1934), the child said to have inspired Lewis Carroll to write his novels. By the 1930s, Alice is an elderly widowed woman who can hardly remember what the author was like.
description: Financial concerns have her visiting the United States for a celebration of Lewis Carroll's centenary. Long forgotten memories of her childhood, Charles Dodgson and his works come flooding back to her and she tries to make sense of them. Meanwhile she also struggles with the fear that her own death is approaching. She comes to realize Dodgson had a secret sorrow and tries to find out what it was. She finally remembers that Charles loved her and would like to marry her. His sorrow was being rejected by young Alice and the rest of the Liddell family. The film ends with what seem to be the ghosts of Dodgson and Alice reunited in the afterlife. While a hit of its time, it is considered controversial because of its implications of pedophilia.
name: Dreamchild

deck: An 1966 musical adaptation of the second novel by Lewis Carroll by NBC. The protagonist was twenty-year-old Judi Rolin. This version added a new character, Lester the Jester. He is considered to be a near-copy of Scarecrow from the Oz stories.
name: Alice through the Looking Glass

deck: An 1966 animated, loose adaptation and parody of the Lewis Carrol tales by Hanna-Barbera Productions. A modern-day teenager doing a book report on Alice, accidentaly is sucked ib by her television set. She ends up in a wacky version of Wonderland.
name: Alice in Wonderland, or What's a Nice Kid Like You Doing in a Place Like This?

deck: An 1965 BBC production in theatrical style. Based on the relationship between Charles Dodgson (Lewis Carroll) and Alice Liddell, portrayed here as one of unrequitted love on Dodgson's part. Various experiences inspire the well-known Wonderland scenes.
name: The Wednesday Play:Alice in Wonderland

deck: An 1955 television version of a well-known Broadway production of Alice, starring teenaged actress Gillian Barber. While there are surviving copies of this television production in various archives, like that of UCLA, they are not commercially available nor in wide circulation,. Making this version one of the most obscure ones.
name: Hallmark Hall of Fame:Alice in Wonderland

deck: An 1938 live-action film with Sonja Henie. Henie was a Norwegian ice skater and multiple times the World Champion of Women's Figure Skating. She received a Hollywood movie contract and starred in various films between 1936 and 1948. Most of her films have thin plots which give excuses for Henie to perform ice skating routines. This one includes her "Alice In Wonderland" skating extravaganza, performed numerous times for live audiences. This seems to be its only record on film.
name: My Lucky Star

deck: An early "talkie" film production from 1930. Harry Richman stars vaudeville and nightclub performer who has trouble handling his own success and turns to drinking. Richman anf female co-star Joan Bennet perform several vaudeville routines, including an Alice one for Bennet. Arguably making her the first talking film version of Alice.
name: Puttin' on the Ritz

deck: An 1931, live-action and talking feature film adaptation of the Lewis arrol tales. While there are reportedly archival copies mentioned in "The American Film Institute Catalog of Motion Pictures Produced in the United States: Feature Films, 1931-1940", there are no known commercially available ones and the preservation status in unknown.
name: Alice in Wonderland

deck: An 1910 production by the Edison Company. Unlike the better known 1915 film, it is not widely available on the internet and might be lost.
name: Alice's Adventures in Wonderland

deck: An 1982 Soviet, animated adaptation of the Lewis Carrol tales.
name: Alisa v Zazerkale

deck: An 1981 Soviet, animated adaptation of the Lewis Carrol tales. Descrived in a favorable review as "Pale, insane, dark, surreal, uncouth, crude, but artistically wonderful."
name: Alisa v strane chudes

deck: An 1966 animated feature film by Gene Deitch. The British Alice visits Paris and encounters other characters from children's literature, such as Anatole by Eve Titus.
name: Alice of Wonderland in Paris

deck: An 1978 short film produced for NBC Television. Instead of Alice, the protagonist is one Amy Patterson (Kelly Ellen Collins). She is a nine-year-old girl bored with her life events seeming to endlessly repeat themselves. A visit to her aunt Lucy leads to encounters with several literary characters and an end to her boredom.
name: Big Apple Birthday

deck: An 1973 Christmas special, adapting the second Lewis Carroll novel. It is considered to be among the most faithfull and literate adaptations. Protagonist Sarah Sutton would later play Nyssa in "Dr. Who".
name: Alice Through the Looking Glass

deck: An 1937 BBC television adaptation of the second Lewis Carroll. Believed to be the earliest television version.
name: Alice Through the Looking Glass

deck: An 1946 BBC production, starring Vivian Pickles.
name: Alice

deck: An animated combilation film, adapting two literary tales: "The Wind in the Willows" by Kenneth Graham and "The Legend of Sleeping Hollow" by Washington Irwing. The latter differs somewhat by implying the Headless Horseman is an actual ghost.
name: The Adventures of Ichabod and Mr. Toad

deck: An 1950 adaptation of the Charles Perrault tale. A daughter of well-to-do family survives her father only to find herself a mere servant to her stepmother and stepsisters.She escapes her fate by winning the heart of a handsome and wealthy Prince. The biggest box-office hit for Disney in over a decade, it helped revitalize the company.
name: Cinderella

deck: An 1953 animated adaptation of the J. M. Barrie stories. Wendy Darling, a young girl of Edwardian era (1901-1910) London, and her siblings are taken to a visit of Neverland by the titular character, a boy refusing to age. While the adaptation loses the philosophical and tragic aspects of the novel, it is widely acclaimed for its sense of adventure and fun.
name: Peter Pan

deck: An 1955 animated film featuring the romance of a female American Cocker Spaniel from an upper-midde class family and a male stray-mutt. A box-office hit in the 1950s but largely dismissed by the critics. Since then its reputation has improved and it is regarded among Disney's quality productions.
name: Lady and the Tramp

deck: An 1957 Soviet adaptation of the Hans Christian Andersen story. The title character  is a cruel queen of the snowflakes who travels throughout the world with the snow. The film concerns the Queen abducting children. It received an English dubbing and American release in 1959.
name: Snow Queen

deck: An 1959 Czechoslovakian adaptation of the William Shakespeare play. In Athens, Theseus and Hippolyta, the Amazon queen are about to wed. Actors preparing to perform for the occassion attend a rehearsal in a nearby forest and encounter magical creatures.
name: A Midsummer Night's Dream

deck: An 1959 animated adaptation of the Charles Perrault tale. Princess Aurora is blessed at her christening by a trio of good fairies but cursed by Maleficent, an evil one angered at being ignored.
description:
Set in 14th century, a celebration occurs in a castle for the king and queen with their baby, Aurora. The three fairies come to christen it. They consist of Flora, Fauna, and Merryweather. Just as she is about to christen Aurora, Merryweather is interrupted by the arrival of evil fairy, Maleficent. Upon find out that she is not invited to the christening, Maleficent curses Aurora that in her 16th birthday, she will die upon pricking her finger in a spindling wheel. Enraged, the king orders the guards to get her, but Maleficent escapes.
 
Merryweather says that she can't break Maleficent's curse, but she can christen Aurora that instead of dying after pricking her finger in a spindling wheel, she will be put into deep sleep.
 
Because of that curse being put by Maleficent, the people begin burning spindling wheels. The king and queen allow the three fairies to pose as aunts of Aurora so that she can be protected.
 
Years later, at Maleficent's hideout, the Forbidden Mountain, she finds out that her minions are only searching for a baby. Enraged by their incompetence, Maleficent attacks them with lightning and sends her pet raven, Diablo, to find Aurora.
 
Meanwhile, Aurora, renamed as Briar Rose, lives a normal life in a hut without knowledge of her past. As she is out, the fairies try to do normal things without magic. Eventually, Merryweather is fed up and Flora reluctantly agrees with using magic.
 
In the forest, Aurora is dancing with Prince Philip.
 
At Aurora's house, Flora and Merryweather got to fight about the color of Aurora's dress that Diablo manages to locate the fairies. When they fixed everything up and Aurora comes home telling them about that she danced a prince, the fairies knew it's about time to tell her the real truth of her past. When they told her that she is forbidden to see Philip again, Aurora goes to her room crying.
 
Meanwhile, Philip tells his father of wishing to marry Aurora, not knowing that she is the princess that his father wants him to marry.
 
In Aurora's castle, Maleficent lures Aurora to touch the spindling wheel, completing the curse. Flora, Fauna, and Merryweather are saddened by this event and puts the entire castle into a deep sleep. While doing so, Flora discovers that Philip is the prince that Aurora has met earlier.
 
In the forest, Philip comes looking for Aurora, but he is captured by Maleficent so that he will not try to kiss her. By the time they got there, Flora, Fauna, and Merryweather finds out that Maleficent has taken Philip to the Forbidden Mountain.
 
They sneak into the Maleficent's castle. Inside, Maleficent goes to the dungeon to meet Philip. In one of the cells, she shows him Aurora and leading him to realize that she is the peasant girl he danced earlier. After Maleficent leave, the three fairies rescue Philip and Flora gives him the Shield of Virtue and Sword of Truth in fighting Maleficent.
 
As they leave, Diablo is shocked to see the fairies and Philip escaping and calls on the guards to get them. However, he is turned to stone by Merryweather.
 
Upon seeing Philip escape, Maleficent tries to take him out with electric bolts, but to no avail. She summons dark thorns so that Philip can't get to the castle. Enraged, Maleficent teleports to Philip and transforms into a black dragon. Philip manages to kill her by throwing his sword to her chest and sending her falling to her death.
 
Philip goes to the castle and kisses Aurora, bringing her back. Afterwards, they danced. However, Flora and Merryweather go to an argument again about the color of Aurora's dress.
name: Sleeping Beauty

deck: An 1955 sequel to Godzilla, the second film of the series. The Godzilla of the first film is dead but a look-alike is discovered  in an uninhabited strip of rocks formed by volcanic eruptions. Soon Godzilla and Anguirus are unleashed in the japanese islands.
description: Godzilla battles Anguris but they both destroy Osaka in the process
name: Godzilla Raids Again

deck: An 1958 Toho film featuring Varan, a new monster, attacking Japan. While not part of the Godzilla series, the film reuses Godzilla footage from the 1954 "Godzilla".
description: This movie is about a giant monster that comes out of a lake. The monster is immune to all the military's weapons. The Monster goes to Japan and creates much disstruction. In the end Varan  is defeated by having bombs dropped in its mouth.
name: Varan the Unbelievable

deck: A 1962 film which has Godzilla clash with King Kong. It was the third Godzilla film and remains the greatest box-office hit in the series.
description: A pharmaceutical company captures King Kong and brings him to Japan, where he escapes from captivity and battles a recently released Godzilla.
name: King Kong vs. Godzilla

deck: A 1964 film featuring the destructive Godzilla facing Mothra who tries to protect humanity. It was the fourth film for Godzilla and the second for Mothra.
description: A greedy developer unwittingly hatches a gigantic baby moth upon Tokyo, while Godzilla strikes once again.
name: Mothra vs. Godzilla

deck: A 1965 featuring the debut of alien monster Ghidorah. Responsible for destroying a thriving civilization on planet Venus, ghidorah arrives on Earth to continue his work. Godzilla, Mothra and Rodan team-up to face the invader.
name: Ghidorah, the Three-Headed Monster

deck: An 1965 film continuing the monster saga of Toho. A combined Japanese and American expedition to Jupiter makes contact with a hidden planet of the Solar System, Planet X. The Xians are revealed to be the creators of Ghidorah and planning to conquer Earth.
description: The American astronaut is called Glenn, possibly in reference to John Glenn.
name: Invasion of Astro-Monster

deck: An 1966 film featuring the return of Godzilla and Mothra. Mothra's home island has been captured by the Red Bamboo, a terrorist organization. The natives try to wake the two sleeping monsters to use in a liberation effort. The terrorists have their own monster, Ebirah the lobster,
name: Godzilla versus the Sea Monster

deck: A 1967 film featuring the birth of Minilla, a baby version of Godzilla. Godzilla senior adopts him but has to protect his offspring from weather-controlling scientists, giant mantises and Kumonga, a giant spider.
name: Son of Godzilla

deck: A 1968 film featuring Godzilla, Mothra, King Ghidorah, Rodan, Gorosaurus, Anguirus, Kumonga, Manda, Minilla, Baragon and Varan. The 20th century is ending and all monsters have been captured and confined on Monster Island. The peace ends when aliens take control of them and unleash them on major cities of the planet.
description: It is the year 1999, and all of Earth's monsters have been captured and put on to Monster Island, but Aliens take control of Earth's monsters and begin using them to destroy the human race.
name: Destroy All Monsters

deck: An 1969 children's film, marking a different direction for the Godzilla series. Ichiro, a lonely Tokyo kid, dreams of Godzilla and Minilla's everyday lives on monster Island and is inspired to face his own everyday problems with courage.
name: All Monsters Attack

deck: An 1971 featuring Godzilla facing Hedorah, a new foe. Hedorah is an alien organism which feeds on pollution and his toxic touch is lethal. Also being a shape-shifter, he proves to be a hard opponent.
name: Godzilla vs. Hedorah

deck: A 1972 film featuring Godzilla defending Earth from an alien invasion. The aliens unleash King Ghidorah along with Gigan, a cyborg monster.
name: Godzilla vs. Gigan

deck: An 1973 entry to the Godzilla series. The undersea civilization of Seatopia has been adversely affected by nuclear testings. They unleash Megalon against the surface dwellers. Godzilla teams-up with the robot Jet Jaguar to face the threat.
name: Godzilla vs. Megalon

deck: An 1974 entry to the Godzilla series. Alien invaders unleash a mechanical version of Godzilla against Earth. The real Godzilla teams-up with King Caesar against his doppelganger.
description: Apelike aliens build a robotic Godzilla to destroy Japan, and the true Godzilla may not be powerful enough to destroy it.
name: Godzilla vs. Mechagodzilla

deck: An 1975 entry to the Godzilla series. The aliens return Mechagodzilla to action and add Titanosaurus, an aquatic dinosaur to the mix. Godzilla is assisted by Katsura Mafune, a female, human cyborg. Due to budget concerns and an oil crisis, this was the last Godzilla film in a decade.
description: Godzilla comes to the rescue when an alien race rebuilds Mechagodzilla to destroy Earth's cities. A traitorous scientist gives them a second weapon known as Titanosaurus.
name: Terror of Mechagodzilla

deck: A 1984 reboot of the Godzilla series. 30 years after the attack of the original, a new, bigger and more powerful Godzilla emerges, and attacks Tokyo.
name: The Return of Godzilla

deck: An 1989 entry to the Godzilla series. Genshiro Shiragami, a genetic scientist, loses his daughter Erika to a terrorist attack. Offered samples of Godzilla's DNA, he combines it with that of Erika and of a common rose to create his own hybrid monster, Biollante.
description: After rising from his volcanic grave, Godzilla is threatened by a mutated rosebush.
name: Godzilla vs. Biollante

deck: A 1991 entry to the rebooted Godzilla series, reintroducing Ghidorah. Time travelers from the year 2204 manipulate events from World War II onwards to ensure the destruction of both Godzilla and Japan itself.
name: Godzilla vs. King Ghidorah

deck: An 1992 entry into the rebooted Godzilla series, reintroducing Mothra and adding a darker counterpart called Battra.
description:
Awards

  • 1993 Tokyo Sports Movie Awards - Best Leading Actor
  • 1993 Best Grossing Films Award - Golden Award and Money-Making Star Award
  • 1993 Awards of The Japanese Academy - Newcomer of The Year: Keiko Imamura, Sayaka Osawa
  • 1993 Awards of The Japanese Academy - Best Music Score: Akira Ifukube
  • 1993 Awards of The Japanese Academy - Best Supporting Actor: Takehiro Murataa
name: Godzilla vs. Mothra

deck: An 1993 entry to the rebooted Godzilla series, reintroducing Godzilla Junior, Mechagodzilla and Rodan.
description: The United Nations assembles the ultimate weapon to defeat Godzilla, while scientists discover a fresh pteranodon egg on a remote Japanese island.
name: Godzilla vs. Mechagodzilla II

deck: An 1994 entry into the Godzilla series. Godzilla faces a clone of himself from space.
name: Godzilla vs. SpaceGodzilla

deck: An 1995 entry to the Godzilla series, intended to be the last one released. Godzilla is dying of a heart condition while Godzilla Junior has grown into an adult. The two face a new foe, Destoroyah. The last battle for the old Godzilla and the first for his heir.
name: Godzilla vs. Destoroyah

deck: An 1998 American remake of Godzilla. A marine iguana mutated by nuclear tests is trying to find a nest for its eggs, choosing New York City. A box office hit but a critical failure, it did revive Toho's interest for the franchise.
name: Godzilla

deck: A 1999 reboot of the Godzilla series, ignoring all Godzilla movies except the original Godzilla film. Sightings of Godzilla are increasing and increasing, then one day, an alien named Orga arrives to Japan, and plans to destroy Japan, but Godzilla emerges to stop the beast.
name: Godzilla 2000: Millennium

deck: An 2000 entry to the Godzilla series. Godzilla is targeted by a species of dragonflies attempting to feed on his energy. He easily defeats them but has to face Megaguirus, the dragonfly queen which has been mutated to reach giant-size.
name: Godzilla vs. Megaguirus

deck: A 2001 film having Godzilla face Baragon, Mothra and King Ghidorah. The Godzilla of this film is powered by an amalgam of tormented souls from World War II. The rival monsters face in a battle of bodies and spiritual energy.
name: Godzilla, Mothra and King Ghidorah: Giant Monsters All-Out Attack

deck: A 2002 entry in the Godzilla series, reintroducing Mechagodzilla. The bones of the 1954 Godzilla are used to create a cyborg intended to defend Japan from the modern version of the monster. However when the Mechagodzilla goes berserk, its creators find him more difficult to handle that his biological counterpart.
name: Godzilla against Mechagodzilla

deck: A 2003 entry in the Godzilla series. A repaired Mechagodzilla and Mothra team-up to defend Japan from Godzilla.
name: Godzilla: Tokyo S.O.S.

deck: The third film in its series that was originally released in 3D. Chris Higgins, a girl attacked by Jason Voorhees three years before, returns to the family farm with her friends. She intends to face her fears. But Jason has picked the farm as a resting spot while recovering from wounds received in Part II.
description:
The masked slasher returns yet again after barely surviving a brutal blow to the shoulder from his own machete.  
 
Jason went to a road side store and grabbed himself a new set of clothes while stalking a new couple before returning to bring death to any who enter "his" woods.  Chris Higgins arrived with her friends back at her old family home where only three years ago she was attacked by Jason. Right from the start Chris had a bad feeling that something or some one is watching them; Jason was now hiding in the barn tending to his wounds.   
 
A group of bikers who had a run in with the teens earlier on started to siphon gas.  Suddenly one of them disappeared inside the barn where he found a hockey mask.  Jason quickly made short work of the biker and claimed the mask as his own.  When their friend didn't return the other two bikers decided to investigate.  When they looked in the barn Jason killed them quickly.  Having stained his infamous machete with new blood and obtaining his infamous mask Jason decided to go on the hunt once again and slowly picked off the unsuspecting teens until only one was left....Chris Higgins.
name: Friday the 13th Part III

deck: The fourth film of the Friday the 13th series. Jason Voorhees has a typical murder spree before getting killed at the hands of siblings Trish and Tommy Jarvis. However young Tommy has a psychotic episode and is hinted to be Jason's successor.
name: Friday the 13th: The Final Chapter

deck: The fifth film of its series. Years have passed since Jason Voorhees was killed with a machete. Tommy Jarvis, the boy responsible, has passed them moving from mental institution to mental institution. When a copycat killer emulating Jason starts killing the patients in Tommy's latest residence, Tommy' fragile sanity is threatened once again.
description: Fifth film in the series.
name: Friday the 13th: A New Beginning

deck: Jason Voorhees is dead and buried for years. This has not prevented him from haunting the fragile mind of Tommy Jarvis. Tommy decides to face his demons by exhuming Jason's corpse. A random lighting bolt then revives the corpse, leaving Jason free to start killing again.
name: Friday the 13th Part VI: Jason Lives

deck: When last seen, Jason Voorhees was trapped with chains in the bottom of Crystal Lake. But he is not the only human body in its depths. Tina Shepard, a telekinetic girl, had drowned her father in the lake. When guilt ridden Tina attempts to raise the corpse of her father, Jason is the one released instead.
name: Friday the 13th Part VII: The New Blood

deck: SS Lazarus is a ship transporting the senior class of Lakeview High to New York City, celebrating their graduation. But there is a stowaway aboard, Jason Voorhees.
description:
Two teens on a fishing trip ended up in Crystal Lake.  There Jason rose up and brutally slashed the young couple into pieces. Taking the boat for himself, Jason floated into a near-by harbour where a large cruise ship sat waiting for its guests to arrive; the graduating class of a near-by high-school who were due to cruise to Manhattan. Jason swam to the ship, and was hauled onboard when the captain drew the anchor.  
 
Onboard the cruise ship, Jason was angrier than ever and quickly started slaughtering all the students who he encountered.  After killing off all but a few of the graduates, the ship stopped in Manhattan. The survivors leapt from the ship and attempt to swim to Manhattan to find help.  They believed Jason was finally dead.  However, no one would believe them, so they were forced to start moving again.  They saw their fears were true; Jason was alive and still pursuing them. Jason continued to hunt the survivors, right down to his final victim.
name: Friday the 13th Part VIII: Jason Takes Manhattan

deck: The ninth film of its series. The body of Jason Voorhees has been destroyed. his spirit continues by taking possession of various human bodies. Only his surviving family members are believed able to lay his spirit to rest. But they can also achieve his rebirth and Jason is pursuing the latter option. Freddy Krueger has a cameo at the end.
name: Jason Goes To Hell: The Final Friday

deck: Two of the most iconic slashers known today battle it out in this blood filled horror in which no matter who walks away, mankind is still in trouble.
description: Freddy has lost his power over the people of Elm Street. He uses Jason to make people believe he is back to regain his power.After Jason has done what he wanted Freddy tries killing Jason because he is not needed for his purposes. He puts him to sleep using his possession abilities to inject Jason with a sleep drug while in the dream world he has Jason beat but something disturbs his killing and with Jason conscious and Freddy out in the real world Freddy battles Jason and loses.
name: Freddy vs. Jason

deck: Freddy's back
description: Five years after Freddy Krueger was thought to be dead, he returns when a family known as the Walshes moves into the former home of Nancy Thompson. Haunting the dreams of the teenage son in the family, Jesse Walsh. Freddy tries to use him to commit murders and to enter the real world. Its up to Jesse and his girlfreind  Lisa Webber to stop Freddy before its too late.
name: Nightmare on Elm Street Part 2: Freddy's Revenge

deck: Freddy Krueger manipulates teenagers to acts of suicide and self-mutilation. Surviving teens are taken to mental hospitals and kept sedated "for their own good". Leaving opportunities for Freddy to have repeat performances. But a mysterious nun tries to stop this reign of terror: Amanda Krueger has returned.
description: Amanda Krueger is the mother of Freddy, revealed at the end of the film to be a ghost.
name: Nightmare on Elm Street 3: Dream Warriors

deck: Kristen Parker has been released from mental hospital, quickly becoming the last surviving of Freddy's Elm Street children. As she makes new friends, Freddy uses her to meet new victims. Kristen's own powers of pulling people into her dreams prove useful for his purposes.
name: Nightmare on Elm Street 4: The Dream Master

deck: A year has passed since Alice Johnson absorbed the dream powers of various persons and used them to defeat Freddy. She suddenly starts reliving the experiences of Amanda Krueger when raped and giving birth to her son. When Alice discovers that she is herself pregnant, she fears Freddy may be reborn.
name: Nightmare on Elm Street 5: The Dream Child

deck: The sixth film of its series. Ten years have passed since the events of the previous one. Freddy has become a victim of his own success. He is trapped in the city of Springwood, Ohio where almost all children and teenagers have either left or died.
description: He uses an amnesiac boy to lure others into Springwood, adding a rare bonus: Dr. Maggie Burroughs, Freddy's only known daughter. The film covers the early history of Freddy, being a child bullied and abused, then growing into an abusive adult. Maggie eventually fights and kills Freddy, delivering the line "Happy Father's Day" right before going for the kill.
name: Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare

deck: The seventh film of its series, it has a twist based on metafiction. Freddy Krueger is only a fictional character and the cast and crew of the original film are celebrating its tenth anniversary. However Freddy has been given life of his own and comes to haunt the dreams of his creators.
name: Wes Craven's New Nightmare

deck: Classic fantasy film, directed by Jim Henson & Frank Oz.
description: Another world, another time, in the age of wonder. A thousand years ago, this land was green and good - until the Crystal cracked. For a single piece was lost; a shard of the Crystal. Then strife began, and two new races appeared: the cruel Skeksis, the gentle Mystics.
name: The Dark Crystal

deck: An 1954 television adaptation of the first James Bond novel. Bond is turned to an American CIA agent,. Love interest Valerie Mathis is a French agent.
name: Casino Royale

deck: A 1962 debut for the James Bond film series. Bond is sent to Jamaica to face Dr. No, a high-ranking SPECTRE agent. Love interest Honey Rider is a shell diver.
name: Dr. No

deck: An 1963 entry to the James Bond series. Bond is send to Turkey to assist Tatiana Romanova, a low-ranking Soviet agent in defecting to Britain. This a set-up by SPECTRE who intend to kill both Bond and Romanova.
name: From Russia with Love

deck: A 1964 entry to the James Bond series. Bond has to face Auric Goldfinger, a businessman intend on destroying Fort Knox and its gold reserves. James seduces Pussy Galore, Goldfinger's chief pilot.
name: Goldfinger

deck: A 1965 entry in the James Bond series. SPECTRE has stolen two nuclear bombs from NATO. Bond has to face Emilio Largo, second-in-command of the organization. He finds an ally in Dominique "Domino" Derval who was already planning to assassinate Largo.
name: Thunderball

deck: An 1967 James Bond spoof, loosely based on the original novel. James Bond is a veteran agent who retired back in World War I. MI6 recalls him back to action to face the rival SMERSH organization. He becomes the New M and shares the codename James Bond with six other agents.
description: The other six Bonds are Evelyn Tremple (a baccarat master),Vesper Lynd (a spy and millionaire businesswoman), Miss Moneypenny, Mata Bond (daughter of James Bond and Mata Hari), Coop and the Detainer (two recently promoted agents).
name: Casino Royale

deck: An 1967 entry in the James Bond series. American and Soviet spacecrafts have been disappearing whle in orbit and the two powers are on the verge of war. MI6 fakes the death of Bond and has him investigating the organization responsible, SPECTRE.
description: Bond first meets Ernst Stavro Blofeld, the head of SPECTRE, in person. Blofeld had cameo appearances in previous films. While in Japan, Bond gains a partner and pretend- wife in Kissy Suzuki.
name: You Only Live Twice

deck: A 1969 entry in the James Bond series. Bond again faces Ernst Stavro Blofeld. This time Blofeld has brainwashed various young girls to be his Angels of Death, distributing bioweapons around the planet
description: Bond meets, romances and marries Contessa Teresa "Tracy" di Vicenzo. Blofeld murders Tracy on their wedding day and Bond is left in tears. She remains the only known wife of Bond.
name: On Her Majesty's Secret Service

deck: An 1971 entry in the James Bond series. Bond investigates a diamond-smuggling network only to discover the diamonds are used to develop laser weaponry. The man responsible is again Ernst Stavro Blofeld. Bond's partner for the case is diamond thief Tiffany Case.
description: Two female assassins in the film use the codenames Bambi and Thumper, in reference to the Disney characters of the same names.
name: Diamonds Are Forever

deck: An 1973 entry in the James Bond series. Bond investigates the major drug-smuggling operation of Mr. Big, a Harlem-based crime lord. To find this is only an alias of Dr. Kananga, dictator of San Monique. Bond is helped by Solitaire, a Haitian psychic. Kananga is assisted by Baron Samedi, a Voodoo sorcerer.
description: Baron Samedi is named after a Voodoo deity of death. In the film he is known as "the man who cannot die". While Bond apparently kills him by throwing him into a snake pit, Samedi appears alive in the finale and laughing demoniacally. The implication is that he is immortal and may not be human at all.
name: Live and Let Die

deck: An 1974 entry in the James Bond series. Bond is targeted by Francisco Scaramanga, a master assassin looking for a challenge. The prize of their fight is a device harvesting solar energy, able to overcome an ongoing energy crisis.
description: Bond is assisted by inept agent Mary Goodnight. A relatively major and competent character appearing in three novels, Goodnight is turned into a joke in her only film appearance.
name: The Man with the Golden Gun

deck: An 1977 entry in the James Bond series. Karl Stromberg plans to trigger World War III  and then recreate human civilzation underwater. Bond teams up with his Soviet counterpart, Anya Amasova of the KGB, to stop him.
description: Amasova remains amost the most competent and popular Bond girls in the series.
name: The Spy Who Loved Me

deck: An 1979 entry in the James Bond series. Hugo Drax plans to annihilate the human race through satellite-launched attacks. Only a hand-full of his agents will survive to breed a master pace in space stations. Bond teams-up with Dr. Holly Goodhead to stop him.
name: Moonraker

deck: An 1981 entry into the James Bond series. Bond has to face Aristotle Kristatos, a Greek smuggler who has stolen a secret communication system from the Royal Navy. This is more of a revenge film focused on the quest of Melina Havelock whose father was killed on orders of Kristatos.
name: For Your Eyes Only

deck: An 1983 entry in the James Bond series. An alliance between Kamal Khan and General Orlov, respectively an exiled Afghan Prince and a renegade Soviet General, smuggles Russian historical treasures to the West. But the duo has more sinister plans.
description: The film is named after its lead female character, Octopussy. She is a circus owner, master jewel smuggler and leader of of an octopus cult whose members were young women.
name: Octopussy

deck: A 1983 remake of "Thunderball". The key difference is the characterization of James Bond. The film has a middle-aged Bond treated as a relic by MI6 and considering his own retirement. There are several references to his mortality.
name: Never Say Never Again

deck: A 1985 entry in the James Bond series. Max Zorin, a French-German businessman, plans to trigger a massive earthquake in the San Andreas Fault, sinking the Silicon Valley to the Pacific Ocean. Bond works with geologist Stacey Sutton to prevent it.
description: Main villain Max Zorin is considered among the strongest villains in the series. But the film received negative reviews for 57-year-old Roger Moore being too old to play Bond and Stacey Sutton being a very weak character. Sutton is depicted as having few actual fighting skills and being very timid, screaming in fear at a drop of a hat. This was a departure from the more competent Bond girls of the 1977-1983 period.
name: A View to a Kill

deck: An 1987 entry in the James Bond series. General Gogol of the KGB (appearing in every Bond film since 1977) has just retired. His successor Leonid Pushkin seem to be much more agressive and his term starts with bloody incidents. But is recently defected Soviet agent Georgi Koskov a reliable source of information?
description: The film involves more cloak-and-dagger than usual. MI6 and Bond have been caught up in an internal conflict among the KGB and who is pulling their strings remains a mystery for much of the film. The leading lady is Kara Milovy, a Czech cellist manipulated to take the fall for a sniper attack.
name: The Living Daylights

deck: The Giant Turtle returns to battle the  monster Legion
name: Gamera 2: Attack of Legion

deck: Gamera battles Iris in the third film in the Hesei era of Gamera
name: Gamera 3: Revenge of Iris

deck: An 1989 entry in the James Bond series. Bond resigns MI6 to go on a personal mission of revenge. He is also caught in a love triangle with Pam Bouvier and Lupe Lamora.
description:
Felix Leiter and Della Churchill are getting married with Bond as their best man. Franz Sanchez, a drug lord, arranges an attack on them for their wedding night. Felix is mutilated and crippled, Della is raped and killed. James wants to take revenge but MI6 is not interested in Sanchez. He resigns from MI6 and goes on a personal mission of revenge, his licence to kill revoked. He gets support from Q, Pam Bouvier (retired CIA agent, turned pilot) and also Lupe Lamora, Sanchez's unwilling sex slave.

The film was the darkest and most violent entry in the series until "Casino Royale" (2006), estranging some fans. Critics and audience have either loved it or hated it.remains the least commercialy succesful Bond film in the United States, thought did better worldwide.
name: Licence to Kill

deck: An 1995 entry in the James Bond series. The Cold War is over and Bond has to adapt to a new world. But his new enemy is a familiar face: Alec Trevelyan, an MI6 agent who faked his death back in 1986. Bond is assisted by Natalya Simonova, a computer programmer.
description: The film followed a six years hiatus due to legal disputes over who owned the rights to the Bond film series. There was an attempt to both modernize bond and humanize him. He is depicted haunted by the deaths of old friends and lovers.
name: GoldenEye

deck: An 1997 entry in the James Bond series. Elliot Carver, a media mogul, orchestrates a conflict between the United States and the People's Republic of China. Bond teams up with Colonel Wai Lin, a Chinese lady spy, to stop the conflict from beginning.
name: Tomorrow Never Dies

deck: An 1999 entry in the James Bond series. Bond is assigned with protecting Electra King, an oil mogul whose father was murdered by Renard, an elusive terrorist. Bond becomes Electra's lover but finds himself sharing the position with Renard. The former terrorist being Elektra's puppet.
description:
Overview

The World is Not enough is the 19th official James Bond film and the third to star Pierce Brosnan as James Bond. The title is derived from a line in both the book and film versions of On Her Majesty's Secret Service, the phrase is the motto of Bond's family. In The World Is Not Enough 007 must protect an oil heiress, Elektra King from a criminal called Renard.

This is Michael Apted's first and only James Bond film. The theme was performed by the band Garbage and the score was written by David Arnold.

Plot

Pre-title sequence

In the pre-title sequence Bond is at a Swiss Bank in Bilbao, Spain, on assignment from M to retrieve a large sum of money from the account of a friend of hers, Sir Robert King-an oil tycoon. While there he questions a banker about the death of his partner, 0012; the man is murdered by his assistant before he can utter a word. Bond escapes and upon his arrival in London, the briefcase explodes at MI6 headquarters, killing Sir Robert. He spots the assassin from the bank and chases after her in a boat chase down The Thames River. He chases her until they arrive at the Millennium Dome where she attempts to escape via use of a hot air balloon. He follows climbing up on the safety line, up there he offers he MI6 protection in return for her cooperation in the investigation of the deaths of Sir Robert King and 0012. She refuses and kills herself by detonating the balloon. Bond lets go of the safety, falling a short distance onto the dome.

Main Plot

While in Scotland attending the funeral of Sir Robert, Bond traces the money back to Renard, a former KGB agent turned terrorist. Bond is told that MI6 once attempted to assassinate Renard but failed, leaving a bullet lodged in Renard's head, the bullet is slowly making it's way through Renard's head gradually taking away his senses giving him an immunity to pain. Bond is then assigned by M to protect King's daughter Elektra; Renard once kidnapped Elektra and MI6 believe he's planning on doing it again.

He flies to Azerbaijan where Elektra is overseeing the construction of a new pipeline stretching from the Caspian Sea to Turkey. While joining Elektra on a tour of the proposed location for the pipeline, Bond and Elektra by a hit squad sent by Renard, equipped with armed para-glider equipped snowmobiles.

Fending off the hit squad Bond pays a visit to an old friend of his, Valentin Zukovsk- a casino owner for information on the attackers.While there he finds that Elektra's head of security, Davidov is in league with Zukovsky. After having sex with Elektra, Bond stows away in Davidov's car to a nearby airstrip. While there Bond kills Davidov in cold blood and sneaks aboard a Russian plane bound for a nuclear weapons facility in Kazakhstan

Posing as a nuclear physicist Bond infiltrates the facility to find out why Renard's men are at an ICBM facility. While there a scientist at the facility, Dr. Christmas Jones follows him as she's suspicious of him and suspects that he's not as he seems. Inside Bond watches Renard remove a locator card from one of the bombs, before he could kill him his cover is blown by Christmas. Renard steals the bomb and flees, leaving his men, the workers, Bond and Jones to die in the explosive laden facility. Bond retrieves the locator card and escapes along with Christmas as the whole facility explodes.

Returning to Azerbaijan Bond informs M that he thinks Elektra may not be as she seems. The two are then interrupted by an unexpected attack on the pipeline; the bomb that Renard stole in Kazakhstan was onboard an inspection rig headed towards the main terminal. Bond and Christmas go after it, entering the pipe on a separate rig. When defusing the bomb Christmas discovers that half the plutonium is missing. Realizing that the whole thing was a set up just to get Bond away from M he orders Christmas to jump off the rig and wait for the explosion.

After the explosion Bond radios in, learning M has been kidnapped. Elektra and Renard then rendezvous at Maidens Tower in Istanbul, Turkey. He presents her with the other half of the plutonium and in return she presents him with M, locked in a small cell. Renard sets an alarm clock down on top of a stool in front of her cell, promising her that she will be killed tomorrow, at noon.

During that same night Bond pays a visit to Zukovsky, at his caviar factory in the Caspian Sea, under the belief that he is working for Elektra. While interrogating him the factory becomes under attack by helicopters, confirming Bond's suspicions. Zukovsky swore that their arrangement was only for Victor III class Submarine, currently being captained by his nephew. If Renard were to take the plutonium he stole and place in the nuclear reactor of the sub, the explosion would level the entire city of Istanbul, sabotaging a Russian pipeline. Elektra's pipeline is supposed to run directly around the city, dramatically increasing the value of her oil. Renard and his men poison the crew of the submarine and then hijacks it.

M, realizing she still has the locator card snatches the alarm clock and uses the battery to power the locator card, sending off a signal with her location to Bond. As Bond leaves, Zukovsky's henchman Mr. Bullion places an explosive to kill Bond. Bond and Christmas escape however but are captured by Bullion and several other men. Bond is placed into a garrote, ancient torture device while Christmas is brought aboard the sub. While Elektra is torturing Bond, Zukovsky storms demanding to know what she's done with his nephew.

Bond makes a gesture towards the table and Zukovsky sees Nikolai's hat; as soon as he realizes he's dead Elektra shoots him. Before he dies Zukovsky fires a shot from his gun concealed in his cane, pretending to fire at Bond but really firing at one of Bond's restraints, freeing him. Bond grabs the gun from Elektra and chases after her, stopping just long enough to free M. Bond asks Elektra to call off the plan but she refuses and he shoots, killing her.

Diving after the sub, Bond boards it and briefly battles with Renard's men and amidst the confusion causes the it to dive rather than surfacing. The submarine hits the sea floor nose on, causing the hull to crack. Catching up to Renard Bond discovers him shoving the plutonium rod into the reactor core, fighting him but loses. He then hoists himself up to the pressure release to reconnect the pressure hose, causing the reactor to backfire; impaling Renard with a nuclear rod. Bond and Christmas make their escape via use of the torpedo tubes, leaving the damaged reactor to safely detonate underwater.

Later that evening, Bond and Christmas enjoy champagne with one another, celebrating the new millennium together in Istanbul. M, joined by the new Q and several other members of the secret service spot Bond by use of a thermal imaging camera.
name: The World Is Not Enough

deck: An 2002 entry to the James Bond series. After spending a year in a North Korean prison, Bond is released only to find that MI6 suspects him of leaking information to the enemy. Bond has to clear his name.
description: Bond has the assistance of Giacinta "Jinx" Johnson and Miranda Frost. Only one of the two ladies is a double agent. While a box office hit, the film received mostly negative reviews. Often criticisms include an over-reliance on special effects and weak characterization. The film managed to anger both North and South Korea due to their depictions. The North is depicted as particularly brutal and war-mongering. The South is depicted as a United States protectorate, to the point of an American giving commands to the South Korean Army.
name: Die Another Day

deck: The infamous Star Wars Holiday Special was only broadcast once, on November 17, 1978. It has never re-aired or been officially released on video.
name: The Star Wars Holiday Special

deck: She swam into films very early and often
name: Dyesebel

deck: Dyesebel returns
name: Anak ni Dyesebel

deck: Dyesebel swims into the modern era
name: Dyesebel

deck: Like Zorro and Robin Hood in the Philippines
name: La Sombra
